Feature: a spike's intent is a falsifiable kill-or-confirm hypothesis before any execution

  Lifecycle stage 1 (Intent) — ADR-029 D1, PDR-016 capability point 1. A spike is
  a first-class unit of work whose intent must be stated as a kill-or-confirm: a
  falsifiable hypothesis plus the assertion(s) that would settle it, scoped to one
  substrate or seam. A vague "evaluate X" is sent back before execution rather than
  run. This is a LEAD-PROCESS behavior: it pins the lead's own spike-intake gate
  (the spike bead lives in the lead registry); there is no BC addressee — the
  question a spike answers is about the lead host's substrate, not a BC's pinned
  behavior. The check is against the spike bead's stated question, the lead's own
  artifact surface (ADR-018).

@scenario_hash:26d217733915954a @lead_integration:spike-lifecycle
  Scenario: a spike whose intent lacks a falsifiable kill-or-confirm hypothesis is sent back before execution
    Given a spike bead filed under an initiative in the lead registry
    And the bead states only an open-ended "evaluate X" goal with no falsifiable hypothesis and no settling assertion
    When the spike is taken up for execution
    Then the spike is sent back to the intent stage before any scratch infra is stood up
    And the bead is required to state a kill-or-confirm hypothesis scoped to one substrate or seam, with at least one assertion that would settle it
